1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,332
Let us begin by looking at a right-angled triangle. This is

2
00:00:04,432 --> 00:00:10,268
a three-four-five triangle, one of the most well-known examples in mathematics.

3
00:00:10,400 --> 00:00:14,200
We can draw squares on each side of the triangle.

4
00:00:14,300 --> 00:00:17,862
The blue square on side a, the green square on

5
00:00:17,962 --> 00:00:21,604
side b, and the red square on the hypotenuse c.

6
00:00:21,800 --> 00:00:26,308
The Pythagorean theorem states that a squared plus b squared

7
00:00:26,408 --> 00:00:30,378
equals c squared. The area of the two smaller squares

8
00:00:30,478 --> 00:00:33,988
together equals the area of the largest square.

9
00:00:36,266 --> 00:00:41,600
Now let us prove this visually by counting areas. A three-by-three

10
00:00:41,700 --> 00:00:47,035
square has nine unit cells. A four-by-four square has sixteen unit

11
00:00:47,135 --> 00:00:52,798
cells. And the hypotenuse square, five-by-five, has twenty-five cells.

12
00:00:53,066 --> 00:00:55,797
Let us now move the nine blue cells from

13
00:00:55,897 --> 00:00:59,830
a-squared into the top-left corner of the c-squared grid.

14
00:01:00,066 --> 00:01:02,944
Now we move the sixteen green cells from

15
00:01:03,044 --> 00:01:07,262
b-squared into the remaining L-shaped region of c-squared.

16
00:01:07,533 --> 00:01:12,534
All twenty-five cells fit perfectly! Nine plus sixteen equals

17
00:01:12,634 --> 00:01:18,137
twenty-five. This proves a-squared plus b-squared equals c-squared.

18
00:01:20,333 --> 00:01:25,907
Now let us prove this algebraically. We construct a large square whose

19
00:01:26,007 --> 00:01:30,609
side length is a plus b. Inside this square, we place four

20
00:01:30,709 --> 00:01:36,121
identical right triangles, each with sides a and b and hypotenuse c.

21
00:01:36,333 --> 00:01:39,940
The area of the large square is a plus b, the

22
00:01:40,040 --> 00:01:45,212
whole squared. This equals the area of the inner c-squared, plus

23
00:01:45,312 --> 00:01:49,001
the four triangles, each of area one-half a b.

24
00:01:49,133 --> 00:01:54,308
Expanding the left side, we get a squared plus two a b plus b

25
00:01:54,408 --> 00:01:59,929
squared. And the right side simplifies to c squared plus two a b.

26
00:02:00,066 --> 00:02:03,791
Now, let us strip off the four triangles from the

27
00:02:03,891 --> 00:02:07,694
diagram. Watch as they slide away from the square.

28
00:02:07,800 --> 00:02:11,345
Subtracting two a b from both sides, we are

29
00:02:11,445 --> 00:02:14,990
left with a squared plus b squared equals c

30
00:02:15,090 --> 00:02:19,484
squared. And that is the Pythagorean theorem, proved!

